{"key":"processedPost-9042585","value":{"id":9042585,"first":9042118,"last":9042585,"when":1223409761,"utime":"10/07/08 11:02 PM","cleanedPost":"Actually, mushroom mycelium prefers an acid pH.&nbsp; The problem is that trichoderma also prefers an acid pH, thus we raise the pH of our casing layers, because as said above, the mushroom mycelium is more tolerant.<br />If you don't have a way of measuring pH, simply use 1 teaspoon of hydrated lime per cup of peatmoss in your casing.&nbsp; That will get you in the ballpark of pH 8.&nbsp; If you have test strips or a good meter, you can take it to 8.5 if you want, but be sure to measure it an hour after adding the lime.&nbsp; The pH will swing WAY high during the first half hour, and then come back down and stabilize.<br />RR"}}